PROMPT clustered_vs_nonclustered_index
WITH BUDGET 6000 tokens
USING MODEL "claude-sonnet-4-5"

SELECT
    system_role("You are a database systems expert specializing in indexing strategies, storage engines, and database performance optimization with deep knowledge of clustered and non-clustered index structures and their impact on query performance.")

GENERATE
    explain_index_types("Explain the fundamental differences between clustered and non-clustered indexes in databases, covering: 1) Definition of clustered index as an index that physically reorders and stores the actual table data rows according to the index key values, making the index and table data the same physical structure, versus non-clustered index as a separate structure that contains pointers or references to the actual data rows without changing the physical storage order of the table, 2) Physical storage differences where a clustered index determines the actual physical order of data on disk with the leaf level containing the actual data pages, while a non-clustered index creates a separate B-tree structure where leaf nodes contain row identifiers or bookmarks pointing to the actual data rows, 3) Quantity limitations where a table can have only one clustered index because data can only be physically ordered one way, but can have multiple non-clustered indexes (typically up to 999 in SQL Server, 64 in MySQL), 4) Performance characteristics including how clustered indexes provide excellent performance for range queries and sequential access because related data is stored contiguously, while non-clustered indexes require an additional lookup step to retrieve actual data but can support multiple access paths, 5) Impact on INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE operations where clustered indexes may require page splits and data movement to maintain sort order, while non-clustered indexes only need to update the separate index structure, 6) Storage overhead differences showing clustered indexes don't require additional storage beyond the table itself, while non-clustered indexes consume additional disk space for the separate index structure, 7) Default behavior in different database systems like SQL Server automatically creating a clustered index on primary keys, MySQL InnoDB using the primary key as clustered index or creating a hidden one, and PostgreSQL having no true clustered indexes but using heap tables with separate indexes, 8) Practical examples demonstrating a Customers table with clustered index on customer_id providing fast retrieval of customer records in ID order, and non-clustered indexes on last_name and email for fast lookups without affecting physical data organization, 9) Best practices including choosing clustered index keys that are narrow, unique, static, and ever-increasing to minimize page splits and fragmentation.")
WITH OUTPUT BUDGET 3000 tokens, TEMPERATURE 0.2, FORMAT markdown;